2. Identify the 3 classes with highest number of images¶

In [ ]:
# Creating a dictionary to store the count of images per class
class_counts = Counter()

# Loop through each class folder in the 'train' directory
for class_folder in os.listdir(os.path.join(data_folder, 'train')):
    class_path = os.path.join(data_folder, 'train', class_folder)
    
    # Count the number of images in each class
    num_images = len(os.listdir(class_path))
    class_counts[class_folder] = num_images

# Identify the top 3 classes with the highest number of images
top_classes = [class_name for class_name, _ in class_counts.most_common(3)]

# Remove unselected classes from the 'train' directory
for class_folder in os.listdir(os.path.join(data_folder, 'train')):
    if class_folder not in top_classes:
        class_path = os.path.join(data_folder, 'train', class_folder)
        shutil.rmtree(class_path)

# Print the top 3 classes
print("Top 3 classes with the highest number of images:")
for class_name in top_classes:
    print(f"{class_name}: {class_counts[class_name]} images")

Copy top three classes to birds_new folder

In [ ]:
# Specify the path to your 'birds' folder
data_folder = pathlib.Path('../data/birds')

# Specify the new path where you want to copy the selected classes
new_folder = pathlib.Path('../data/birds_new')

# Create new subfolders in the new structure
for subfolder in ['train', 'test', 'valid']:
    new_subfolder_path = new_folder / subfolder
    new_subfolder_path.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)

# Loop through each subfolder
for subfolder in ['train', 'test', 'valid']:
    subfolder_path = data_folder / subfolder
    
    # Loop through selected classes
    for selected_class in top_classes:
        class_name = selected_class
        
        # Check if the class folder exists
        class_folder_path = subfolder_path / class_name
        if class_folder_path.exists():
            # Create a new folder in the new path
            new_class_folder_path = new_folder / subfolder / class_name
            new_class_folder_path.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
            
            # Copy all files from the original class folder to the new folder
            for file_name in os.listdir(class_folder_path):
                file_path = class_folder_path / file_name
                shutil.copy(file_path, new_class_folder_path)

# Print a message indicating that the copy is complete
print(f"Selected classes copied to {new_folder}")

Data Augmentation

In [ ]:
augmented_data = ImageDataGenerator(
    rotation_range=20,
    shear_range=0.2,
    zoom_range=0.2,
    horizontal_flip = True,
    fill_mode = 'nearest'
)

test_datagen = ImageDataGenerator()

train_generator = augmented_data.flow_from_directory(
    train_path,
    target_size=(224,224),
    batch_size=32,
    class_mode='categorical',
)

validation_generator = augmented_data.flow_from_directory(
    valid_path,
    target_size=(224,224),
    batch_size=32,
    class_mode='categorical',
)


test_generator = test_datagen.flow_from_directory(
    test_path,
    target_size=(224,224),
    batch_size=32,
    class_mode='categorical',
)

5. Defining a Full Model¶

In [ ]:
inputs = keras.Input(shape=(224, 224, 3))
x = keras.applications.vgg16.preprocess_input(inputs)
x = conv_base(x)
x = layers.Flatten()(x)
x = layers.Dense(128)(x)
outputs = layers.Dense(3, activation="softmax")(x)
model = keras.Model(inputs, outputs)

Evaluate the model

In [ ]:
def model_eval(model,test_data):
    # Make predictions
    predictions = model.predict(test_data) 
    # Convert predictions to class labels
    y_pred = np.argmax(predictions, axis=1)
    # True labels
    y_test = test_generator.classes
    
    eval = {}
    eval['Accuracy'] = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)*100
    eval['Precision'] = precision_score(y_test, y_pred, average='weighted')*100
    eval['Recall'] = recall_score(y_test, y_pred, average='weighted')*100
    eval['f1 score'] = f1_score(y_test, y_pred, average='weighted')*100
    for k,v in eval.items():
        print(f"{k}\t{v:.2f}")
    return y_test,y_pred

Precision recall curve and its area under the curve (AUC)

In [ ]:
from keras.utils import to_categorical
# prediction labels
pred = model.predict(test_generator)

# True labels
true = test_generator.classes
true = to_categorical(true)
for i in range(3):
    actual = true[:, i]
    predictions = pred[:, i]
    precision, recall, _ = precision_recall_curve(actual, predictions)
    label = f"[{img_labels[i]}] AUC = {auc(recall, precision):.2f}"
    plt.plot(recall,precision,lw=2,label=label)

plt.xlabel("Recall")
plt.ylabel("Precision")

misclassified_indices = np.where(y_pred != y_test)[0]

# Reset the generator
test_generator.reset()

plt.figure(figsize=(15, 15))
for idx, i in enumerate(misclassified_indices):
    # Retrieve the misclassified image and true label from the test generator
    img_batch, true_labels = test_generator[i]
    img = img_batch[0]  # Extract the image from the batch

    # Extract the true label using argmax
    true_label = np.argmax(true_labels)

    # Display the misclassified image with true and predicted labels
    plt.subplot(4, 5, idx + 1)
    plt.imshow(img.astype("uint8"))
    plt.title(f"Actual: {img_labels[true_label]}\nPredicted: {img_labels[y_pred[i]]}", fontsize=8)
    plt.axis("off")

    108     if self.seed is not None:
    109         np.random.seed(self.seed + self.total_batches_seen)

ValueError: Asked to retrieve element 1, but the Sequence has length 1

CONCLUSIONS¶

  • Model is performing good at train and validation set, but very worst on test set.
  • The model may be underfitting due to less number of data for deep learning.
